Wow,

Thank you all for the kind words!
If we get more this weekend I will add to it.

Cassidy (7) asked last night when she gets a job and if she could work for
me. We have a toy/baby business also.
I had to hug her. I told her "yes, but your already helping me it just
doesn't look like work when you like what you do."

Finding unschooling when Dustin left school years ago changed my life so
much. I never realized that by supporting my children I too would find my way.
(tears of joy:)


Laura

messages.msgSnippet: Thank you, We raise Brittanys and sell children s products. Nice mix huh? If you went to Peabody Kelly mentioned our dog business in one of her sessions which
messages.messageBody:
Thank you,




We raise Brittanys and sell children's products. Nice mix huh?
If you went to Peabody Kelly mentioned our dog business in one of her
sessions which I thought was pretty awesome!

There should be a "home" link on the page so you can see what they look like
older than a few minutes.

Several years of 1-2 litters a year and holding the camera while trying to
make sure everyone is breathing and not being crushed by mom who is now
exhausted doesn't net many great images. I love the paw and detail on the sac also.
I could do without the icky one but in order to show the process it kinda
needs to be there. Or shall I say I fear someone taking issue with that one. I
have never disallowed my the moms from eating them.

In one of those images is a male pup who was not moving or breathing. I
think the last left. The shake down technique and some suction worked well along
with bit of panic:) I've never lost a puppy so when he began moving I was
yelling pongo and perty 8 puppies! A day whelp with all the kids home and me
alone was interesting. Cameron our 3 yr old was in the whelping box beside me
gasping in awe of it all.

They are so cute!
Mom and pups are doing wonderful.

Laura

messages.msgSnippet: amazing!  thanks for sharing that.  the picture of the paw through the sac is so beautiful. i don t think it s gross that animals eat the placenta.  many human
messages.messageBody:
amazing! thanks for sharing that. the picture of the paw through the sac
is so beautiful.

i don't think it's gross that animals eat the placenta. many human cultures
do as well and with good reason...it's full of beneficial hormones to ease
and speed healing. many people make remedies from dried placenta to treat
postpartum depression quite effectively.

chandelle'
